Proof.: The first is to expand Eq. 1 by using definitions mentioned in Section 3.

\[\begin{split} f_{TD}(\mathbf{X})&=\mathtt{Concat}\left( \bar{\mathbf{X}}_{1},\ldots,\bar{\mathbf{X}}_{H}\right)\bar{\mathbf{W}}\\ &=\sum_{h=1}^{H}\bar{\mathbf{X}}_{h}\bar{\mathbf{W}}_{i\sim j},i:=( h-1)*C,j:=h*C,\end{split} \tag{4}\]

where \(\bar{\mathbf{W}}_{i\sim j}\) is a slice of weights \(\bar{\mathbf{W}}\) with \(C\) entries, and we have

\[\bar{\mathbf{X}}_{h}=\mathtt{Softmax}\left((\mathbf{X}\bar{\boldsymbol{\alpha} }_{h})(\mathbf{X}\bar{\boldsymbol{\beta}}_{h})^{T}+f_{mask}(\mathbf{D}^{h}) \right)(\mathbf{X}\bar{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}_{h})\,. \tag{5}\]

In plain words, \(\mathtt{Softmax}\) in the above equation is the standard softmax operation that only involves \(h\)-hop connected columns and applies on every row, then it produces a self-attention matrix \(\mathbf{S}\in\mathbb{R}^{N\times N}\), where

\[\mathbf{S}_{ij}=\begin{cases}\mathtt{Softmax}\left(x_{i}\right)_{j}&\text{if }j\in\text{ argtrue}\mathbf{D}^{h}_{i,.},\\ 0&\text{otherwise}.\end{cases} \tag{6}\]

where \(x\) denotes the term inside \(\mathtt{Softmax}\) in Eq. 5. Then

\[f_{TD}(\mathbf{X})_{i}=\sum_{h=1}^{H}\sum_{j\in\text{argtrue}\mathbf{D}^{h}_{i.}}\mathbf{S}_{ij}\mathbf{X}_{j}\bar{\boldsymbol{\gamma}}_{h}\bar{\mathbf{W}}_ {i\sim j}. \tag{7}\]

Herein, this proof is transformed to representing node sets of all pathways by \(\{\text{argtrue}\mathbf{D}^{h}_{i,.}\}_{h=1,\ldots,H}\), i.e., the following Lemma

**Lemma A.1**.: _The node collection of half of the neural pathways within \(H\)-hop started at the \(i\)-th node can be sorted as \(\mathbf{P}^{H}_{i}\in\{\text{argtrue}\mathbf{D}^{h}_{i,.}\}_{h=1,\ldots,H}\), where 'collection' denotes a set allowing repeated members._

To prove this Lemma, there is an easy fact that can be seen. If \(\forall i\) the degree \(\mathbf{D}_{i}>0\), then

\[(\hat{\mathbf{A}}^{\mathbf{S}})^{h}_{ij}>0\Longrightarrow(\hat{\mathbf{A}}^{ \mathbf{S}})^{h+2}_{ij}>0,\forall h>0 \tag{8}\]

This is true since \(\forall 1\leq i\leq N,(\hat{\mathbf{A}}^{\mathbf{S}})^{2}_{ii}>0\). Then, given that \(\mathbf{D}^{h}_{i,.}:=\left((\hat{\mathbf{A}}^{\mathbf{S}})^{h}>0\right) \cdot\left(\hat{\mathbf{A}}^{\mathbf{F}}\right)\) and \(\hat{\mathbf{A}}^{\mathbf{F}}\) remains unchanged with various \(h\), we can have the same deduction on detour adjacency matrix

\[\mathbf{D}^{h}_{ij}>0\Longrightarrow\mathbf{D}^{h+2}_{ij}>0,\forall h>0 \tag{9}\]

