Given Eq. 9, \(\forall\mathbf{D}^{H}_{ij}>0\), the \(j\)-th node will present accumulated on every other hop adjacency matrix, i.e., \(\mathbf{\hat{A}}^{\mathbf{D}_{k}}_{ij}>0\) if \(k=h+2t\) and \(t\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}\). Thus, the node index \(j\) as a member of multiple/single pathways with at least a length of \(h\) appears \((H-h)//2+1\) times.

Assuming a path sub-graph starts at \(i\)-th node ends at \(h\)-hop and has the node index collection \(\{i+1,i+2,\cdots,i+t,\cdots,i+h\}\) regardless of the starting node, then in this case,

\[\mathbf{P}^{H}_{i}=\{[i+t]*((h-t)//2+1)\}_{t=1,\cdots,h}, \tag{10}\]

where \([\cdot]*x\) means repeating elements \(x\) times in a collection. Since the entire node index collection of one path is \(\{[i+t]*(h-t+1)\}_{t=1,\cdots,h}\), \(\mathbf{P}^{H}_{i}\) can be sorted as exactly the half of all simple paths in this path sub-graph if it contains even number of nodes, or half + 1 if the number is odd. Consequently, we can make a deduction from one path to all non-overlap paths started at \(i\)-th node, where the definition of the neural pathway in our work is the non-overlap paths.

Taking Eq. 7 and Lemma A.1 together, \(f_{TD}(\mathbf{X})_{i}\) weights all nodes of half of the neural pathways by sorting results \(\mathbf{P}^{H}_{i}\). By assigning each node with the learnable weights \(\mathbf{S}_{ij}\overline{\gamma}_{h}\mathbf{\hat{W}}_{i\sim j}\) since \(\mathbf{S}_{ij}\) is a scalar that can be moved aside to matrices, each path weights is thus represented by this weight consists of learnable parameters and can be extracted to explain the contribution by neural pathways to any downstream application. This can finish the proof. 

